@performance/hp-arkui-no-state-var-acces.content:
**Failure Pattern (Most Common)**: LLMs often misidentify the target location when fixing @State variable abuse in loops. They incorrectly apply optimizations to the build() function's ForEach loops instead of fixing the actual procedural logic (e.g., for/while loops in onClick handlers).

**Why This Fails**:
- In ArkUI's declarative build() function, @State variables MUST remain reactive to drive UI updates.
- Extracting @State variables to local const in ForEach loops breaks ArkUI's reactivity mechanism and causes UI not to update.

**Correct Approach**:
1. **Identify the target**: The alarm is in PROCEDURAL code (onClick, lifecycle methods, utility functions), NOT in build()
2. **Extract to local variable**: Only extract @State reads in the procedural loop, NOT in ForEach
3. **Preserve reactivity**: Never touch @State variables in build() unless you understand ArkUI's reactivity model

**Example**:
```typescript
// WRONG: Extracting in build()'s ForEach - breaks reactivity
build() {
  const localItems = this.items; // ❌ Breaks UI updates
  ForEach(localItems, (item) => { ... })
}

// CORRECT: Extract only in procedural loops
onClick() {
  const localItems = this.items; // ✅ Correct location
  for (let i = 0; i < localItems.length; i++) { ... }
}
```

@performance/hp-arkui-use-reusable-compo.content:
**Failure Pattern (Stereotyped Decorator Injection)**: LLMs blindly add @Reusable to ALL visible @Component structs at the file's top level, without understanding which component is actually being iterated in LazyForEach.

**Why This Fails**:
- @Reusable must be applied to the component that is DIRECTLY instantiated inside LazyForEach's item builder.
- Adding @Reusable to the page's root component (e.g., @Entry struct) has no effect and wastes performance.

**Correct Approach**:
1. **Locate LazyForEach**: Find the LazyForEach call in the code
2. **Identify iterated content**: Look at what's being created inside the itemBuilder callback
3. **Extract as @Reusable component**: If it's inline UI, extract it into a separate @Component struct
4. **Place @Reusable**: Add @Reusable decorator ONLY to the extracted component

**Example**:
```typescript
// WRONG: Decorating the wrong component
@Reusable  // ❌ This is the page root, not the iterated item!
@Entry
@Component
struct MyPage {
  build() {
    List() {
      LazyForEach(data, (item) => {
        ListItem() {
          // Complex UI here... (THIS is what needs @Reusable)
        }
      })
    }
  }
}

// CORRECT: Extract and decorate the iterated component
@Component
struct MyPage {
  build() {
    List() {
      LazyForEach(data, (item) => {
        ReusableItem({ data: item })  // ✅ Using reusable component
      })
    }
  }
}

@Reusable  // ✅ Correct placement
@Component
struct ReusableItem {
  @State data: ItemData = null;
  aboutToReuse(params) { this.data = params.data; }  // Required!
  build() { /* Complex UI */ }
}
```

**Failure Pattern (Incomplete Lifecycle Hooking)**: LLMs add @Reusable decorator but forget to implement the mandatory aboutToReuse(params) lifecycle callback.

**Why This Fails**:
- @Reusable components are recycled and reused for different data items.
- Without aboutToReuse(), the component shows stale data from previous items.
- This causes visual bugs: scrolling lists show wrong data.

**Correct Approach**:
1. **Always pair @Reusable with aboutToReuse()**: These must go together.
2. **Update ALL state variables**: In aboutToReuse(params), reassign all @State/@Link properties with new data.
3. **Match parameter names**: Ensure params keys match the property names.

**Template**:
```typescript
@Reusable
@Component
struct MyReusableItem {
  @State title: string = '';
  @State count: number = 0;
  @State isActive: boolean = false;

  // MANDATORY: Update state when component is reused
  aboutToReuse(params: Record<string, ESObject>) {
    this.title = params.title as string;
    this.count = params.count as number;
    this.isActive = params.isActive as boolean;
  }

  build() {
    Row() {
      Text(this.title)
      Text(`${this.count}`)
    }
  }
}
```

**Checklist**:
- [ ] Added @Reusable decorator
- [ ] Implemented aboutToReuse(params: Record<string, ESObject>)
- [ ] Updated all @State/@Link variables in aboutToReuse
- [ ] Tested scrolling to verify no stale data

**Failure Pattern (Cross-Ecosystem Knowledge Transfer)**: LLMs apply React/Vue best practices that are incompatible with ArkUI's @Reusable mechanism.

**ArkUI @Reusable Constraints**:

1. **NO Functions as Parameters**:
   - In React: onClick={(e) => handleClick(e)} is fine.
   - In ArkUI: Passing ANY function to @Reusable components breaks reuse pool.
   - Solution: Use event emitters or global state management instead.

```typescript
// WRONG: Function parameter breaks @Reusable
@Reusable
struct Item {
  onItemClick: (id: string) => void;  // ❌ Function parameter
}

// CORRECT: Use event or callback pattern
@Reusable
struct Item {
  itemId: string;
  build() {
    Row().onClick(() => {
      getContext(this).eventHub.emit('itemClick', this.itemId); // ✅
    })
  }
}
```

2. **Avoid @Prop for Complex Objects**:
   - @Prop creates deep copies, negating reuse performance benefits.
   - Prefer @State with manual updates in aboutToReuse().

```typescript
// LESS IDEAL: Deep copy overhead
@Reusable
struct Item {
  @Prop item: ComplexObject;  // Creates deep copy on each reuse
}

// BETTER: Manual state management
@Reusable
struct Item {
  @State itemData: ComplexObject = null;
  aboutToReuse(params) {
    this.itemData = params.item;  // Shallow reference, faster
  }
}
```

**CRITICAL FAILURE PATTERN**: The most common and persistent failure when adding @Reusable is trying to keep nested custom components. LLMs repeatedly fail by attempting to 'wrap' custom component calls in @Builder methods, not understanding that this does NOT solve the problem.

**Core Rule (Non-negotiable)**:
- A @Reusable component's build() method can ONLY contain:
  1. Built-in UI components (Row, Column, Stack, Text, Image, List, Grid, etc.)
  2. Calls to @Builder methods that themselves only contain built-in UI components
  3. Control flow (if/else, ForEach) with built-in components
- **ANY custom component instantiation (MyComponent({ ... })) will trigger @performance/hp-arkui-replace-nested-reusable-component-by-builder warning**

**Why @Builder Does NOT Fix Nesting**:
```typescript
// ❌ WRONG - This STILL triggers the warning
@Reusable
@Component
struct Parent {
  @Builder buildChild() {
    ChildComponent({ data: this.data });  // ❌ Custom component in @Builder
  }
  build() {
    this.buildChild();  // ❌ Warning persists
  }
}
```
CodeLinter detects custom component instantiation anywhere in the component (build() or @Builder methods), not just in build(). @Builder is for organizing UI code with BUILT-IN components, not for wrapping custom components.

**Required Solution: Complete Inlining**:
When you have nested custom components, you MUST:
1. Completely remove the nested custom component struct definition (or stop using it)
2. Lift ALL state variables (@State, @Prop, @Link, private vars) from nested component to parent
3. Lift ALL methods (lifecycle: aboutToAppear/aboutToDisappear, private methods) to parent
4. Move ONLY the UI building code (content of nested component's build() method) into @Builder methods
5. Replace custom component calls with @Builder method calls

**Complete Example**:
```typescript
// BEFORE: Nested custom components
@Component
struct VideoSwipeComponent {
  @Prop index: number;
  private datasource?: DataSource;

  build() {
    if (this.datasource?.type === 'video') {
      VideoPlayer({ index: this.index, data: this.datasource });  // Nested
    } else {
      CustomView({ data: this.datasource });  // Nested
    }
  }
}

@Component
struct VideoPlayer {
  @Prop index: number;
  @State playerState: PlayerState = PlayerState.IDLE;
  private player: AVPlayer = new AVPlayer();

  aboutToAppear() { this.player.init(); }
  aboutToDisappear() { this.player.release(); }

  build() {
    Stack() {
      XComponent({ id: 'player', controller: this.xController });
      if (this.playerState !== PlayerState.PLAYING) {
        Image($r('app.media.play_icon'));
      }
    }
  }
}

// AFTER: Fully inlined with @Reusable
@Reusable
@Component
struct VideoSwipeComponent {
  @Prop index: number;
  private datasource?: DataSource;

  // ✅ Lifted all VideoPlayer state
  @State playerState: PlayerState = PlayerState.IDLE;
  private player: AVPlayer = new AVPlayer();

  aboutToReuse(params: Record<string, ESObject>) {
    this.index = params.index as number;
  }

  // ✅ Lifted lifecycle methods with conditional logic
  aboutToAppear() {
    if (this.datasource?.type === 'video') {
      this.player.init();
    }
  }

  aboutToDisappear() {
    if (this.datasource?.type === 'video') {
      this.player.release();
    }
  }

  // ✅ @Builder with ONLY built-in components (UI from VideoPlayer.build())
  @Builder
  buildVideoPlayer() {
    Stack() {  // ✅ Built-in Stack
      XComponent({ id: 'player', controller: this.xController });  // ✅ Built-in XComponent
      if (this.playerState !== PlayerState.PLAYING) {
        Image($r('app.media.play_icon'));  // ✅ Built-in Image
      }
    }
  }

  @Builder
  buildCustomView() {
    Column() {  // ✅ Built-in Column
      // Custom builder from datasource (not a custom component)
      this.datasource?.customBuilder?.builder();
    }
  }

  build() {
    if (this.datasource?.type === 'video') {
      this.buildVideoPlayer();  // ✅ Calls @Builder, no custom component
    } else {
      this.buildCustomView();  // ✅ Calls @Builder, no custom component
    }
  }
}
```

**Inlining Checklist** (MANDATORY for @Reusable with nested components):
- [ ] All @State/@Prop/@Link variables from nested components moved to parent level
- [ ] All private variables and properties moved to parent level  
- [ ] All aboutToAppear/aboutToDisappear methods moved to parent with conditional type checks
- [ ] All private/helper methods moved to parent level
- [ ] Created @Builder methods containing ONLY the UI code (build() content) from nested components
- [ ] @Builder methods contain NO custom component instantiation - only built-in UI components
- [ ] Parent's build() calls @Builder methods instead of custom components
- [ ] aboutToReuse() updates all lifted state properties
- [ ] Verified with codelinter that no @performance/hp-arkui-replace-nested-reusable-component-by-builder warnings remain

**When Inlining is Too Complex**:
If nested components are extremely complex (300+ lines each), consider:
1. NOT using @Reusable on the parent component (if performance is acceptable)
2. Refactoring the component hierarchy to reduce nesting depth
3. Breaking the large component into multiple separate @Reusable siblings in LazyForEach

However, for most real-world cases (like the VideoSwipeComponent example which had 360-line nested components), complete inlining IS the required and correct solution.

**CRITICAL FAILURE PATTERN**: After adding @Reusable and extracting the component correctly, DA L3 still fails because the new @Reusable struct introduces `@performance/hp-arkui-suggest-reuseid-for-if-else-reusable-component`.

**Why .reuseId() Does NOT Fix This**:
The linter rule fires on the component's instantiation callsite when it detects any if-else in ANY method of the @Reusable struct — including @Builder methods. Using `.reuseId(item.condition ? 'a' : 'b')` at the callsite does NOT suppress the warning. The warning fires regardless of whether reuseId is present or absent.

**Verified Behavior** (codelinter 6.0.240):
```typescript
@Reusable
@Component
struct BatchSelectRecentListItem {
  @Builder buildContent() {
    Row() {
      if (StringUtil.isEmpty(this.item.suffix)) {  // ← Triggers suggest-reuseid
        Image(...)
      } else {
        Text(...)
      }
    }
  }
  build() {
    ListItem() { this.buildContent() }  // No if-else in build()
  }
}
// Even with .reuseId('recent-item') at callsite, warning still fires on the callsite line.
```

**The Only Reliable Fix: Replace ALL structural if-else with .visibility() ternary**

This applies to EVERY method in the @Reusable struct:

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG — triggers suggest-reuseid even though it's in @Builder, not build()
@Builder buildPortrait() {
  if (StringUtil.isEmpty(this.suffix)) {
    Image($r('app.media.ic_user_portrait'))
  } else {
    Text(this.suffix.toUpperCase())
  }
}

// ✅ CORRECT — both nodes always in tree, toggled by Visibility
@Builder buildPortrait() {
  Image($r('app.media.ic_user_portrait'))
    .visibility(StringUtil.isEmpty(this.suffix) ? Visibility.Visible : Visibility.None)
  Text(this.suffix.toUpperCase())
    .visibility(StringUtil.isEmpty(this.suffix) ? Visibility.None : Visibility.Visible)
}
```

And in build():
```typescript
// ❌ WRONG — triggers suggest-reuseid
build() {
  ListItem() {
    Stack() {
      this.buildContent()
      if (this.showDivider) { Divider() }  // ← triggers warning
    }
  }
}

// ✅ CORRECT
build() {
  ListItem() {
    Stack() {
      this.buildContent()
      Divider()
        .visibility(this.showDivider ? Visibility.Visible : Visibility.None)
    }
  }
}
```

**Exceptions — if-else that does NOT trigger the rule**:
- Inside event callbacks: `onClick(() => { if (x) { ... } })` — these are procedural JS, not UI tree construction, and are safe to keep.
- The linter specifically checks for UI component construction nodes inside conditional branches.

**Rule Chain Awareness**:
Fixing `hp-arkui-use-reusable-component` cascades into:
1. `hp-arkui-replace-nested-reusable-component-by-builder` — if custom components remain
2. `hp-arkui-suggest-reuseid-for-if-else-reusable-component` — if structural if-else remain
All three must be resolved in a single patch for DA L2+L3 to pass.

**DA L3 Note on Line Shifts**:
Adding ~200-300 lines of new @Reusable struct code will shift pre-existing violation line numbers. DA L3's exact (file, line, rule) tuple comparison will flag these shifts as "new violations" even though the underlying rules are unchanged. This is a DA L3 implementation limitation, NOT a regression in the fix.

**CRITICAL FAILURE PATTERN**: LLMs frequently misunderstand when `.reuseId()` is required. They incorrectly assume that if a @Reusable component internally uses if/else to handle different data types, the LazyForEach callsite does NOT need `.reuseId()` because "it's a single component type." This is WRONG.

**Core Rule (Non-negotiable)**:
- If a @Reusable component's `build()` method contains **ANY conditional rendering** (if/else, switch, ternary operators that affect UI structure), the LazyForEach callsite **MUST** call `.reuseId()` to differentiate the rendering paths.
- This applies even when the component appears to be "one type" - what matters is whether different items can produce different UI structures.

**Why This Rule Exists**:
ArkUI's component recycling pool needs explicit type discrimination when a single @Reusable component can render in structurally different ways. Without `.reuseId()`, the framework may reuse a component instance configured for one rendering path (e.g., video player UI) to display another path (e.g., custom view UI), causing visual corruption and state inconsistencies.

**Related Linter Rule**: `@performance/hp-arkui-suggest-reuseid-for-if-else-reusable-component`

**Common LLM Reasoning Errors**:

1. **Error: "It's a single component, so no reuseId needed"**
   ```typescript
   // LLM sees this and thinks: "VideoSwipeComponent is one component type, 
   // the if/else is internal implementation, so reuseId not needed"
   @Reusable
   @Component
   struct VideoSwipeComponent {
     build() {
       if (this.datasource?.type === 'video') {
         this.buildVideoPlayer();  // Different UI structure
       } else {
         this.buildCustomView();   // Different UI structure
       }
     }
   }

   // LLM incorrectly generates:
   LazyForEach(this.datasource, (item, index) => {
     VideoSwipeComponent({ datasource: item })  // ❌ Missing .reuseId()
   })
   ```
   **Why This Fails**: Even though it's "one component," the two branches produce radically different widget trees. ArkUI cannot safely reuse a component instance from one branch to render the other.

2. **Error: "reuseId is only for different component types"**
   LLMs think `.reuseId()` is only needed when LazyForEach switches between `ComponentA()` and `ComponentB()`, not when a single component has internal branching.

**CORRECT Understanding**:
`.reuseId()` is required whenever:
- The @Reusable component's build() uses if/else/switch/ternary for UI structure
- Different data items could take different branches
- The component is instantiated in a LazyForEach loop

**Correct Fix**:
```typescript
@Reusable
@Component
struct VideoSwipeComponent {
  private datasource?: VideoSwipePlayerDataSource | CustomSwipePlayerDataSource;

  build() {
    if (this.datasource?.type === 'video') {
      this.buildVideoPlayer();   // Branch 1: Video UI
    } else {
      this.buildCustomView();    // Branch 2: Custom UI
    }
  }
}

// Parent component with LazyForEach
@Component
struct SwipePlayer {
  build() {
    Swiper() {
      LazyForEach(this.datasource, (item: VideoSwipePlayerDataSource | CustomSwipePlayerDataSource, index: number) => {
        VideoSwipeComponent({
          index: index,
          datasource: item,
          curIndex: this.curIndex,
          // ... other params
        })
        .reuseId(item.type)  // ✅ MANDATORY: Differentiates video vs custom rendering paths
      })
    }
  }
}
```

**How to Determine reuseId Value**:
1. **Identify the discriminating property**: What field determines which branch is taken? (e.g., `item.type`, `item.category`, `item.kind`)
2. **Use that property as reuseId parameter**: `.reuseId(item.type)` or `.reuseId(item.category)`
3. **Ensure uniqueness within structural variants**: The value should be stable and distinguish all rendering paths

**Complete Fix Checklist**:
- [ ] Component has @Reusable decorator
- [ ] Component's build() contains if/else or other conditional rendering
- [ ] Identified the discriminating field (e.g., `datasource.type`)
- [ ] Added `.reuseId(item.discriminatingField)` to LazyForEach callsite
- [ ] Verified no `@performance/hp-arkui-suggest-reuseid-for-if-else-reusable-component` warnings remain

**Real-World Example**:
```typescript
// BEFORE: Missing reuseId despite conditional rendering
@Reusable
@Component
struct VideoSwipeComponent {
  build() {
    if (this.datasource?.type === 'video') {
      // 360+ lines of video player UI (XComponent, Image, controls)
      this.buildVideoPlayer();
    } else {
      // Custom view UI (different widget structure)
      this.buildCustomView();
    }
  }
}

// Parent LazyForEach - MISSING reuseId
LazyForEach(this.datasource, (item, index) => {
  VideoSwipeComponent({ datasource: item })  // ❌ Triggers lint warning
})

// AFTER: Added reuseId to fix
LazyForEach(this.datasource, (item, index) => {
  VideoSwipeComponent({ 
    datasource: item,
    index: index 
  })
  .reuseId(item.type)  // ✅ Fixes @performance/hp-arkui-suggest-reuseid-for-if-else-reusable-component
})
```

**Edge Cases**:

1. **Multiple conditions**: If build() has multiple if/else levels, identify the TOP-LEVEL discriminator:
   ```typescript
   build() {
     if (this.item.category === 'A') {
       // Further nested if/else here
       if (this.item.subType === 'X') { ... }
       else { ... }
     } else { ... }
   }
   // Use: .reuseId(this.item.category)  // Top-level discriminator
   ```

2. **No conditional rendering**: If build() has NO branching (no if/else/switch), `.reuseId()` is NOT needed:
   ```typescript
   @Reusable
   @Component
   struct SimpleItem {
     build() {
       Row() { Text(this.title) }  // No branching
     }
   }
   // LazyForEach callsite: NO .reuseId() needed
   ```

3. **Conditional styling only**: If if/else only changes styling (colors, sizes) but NOT widget structure, `.reuseId()` is usually NOT needed, but follow linter guidance.

